        <h1>Amoeba</h1>
        <p>Amoeba is a two-player <a href="https://hu.wikipedia.org/wiki/T%C3%A1rsasj%C3%A1t%C3%A9k#A_t%C3%A1rsasj%C3%A1t%C3%A9kok_oszt%C3%A1lyoz%C3%A1sa" target="_blank">abstract strategy board game,</a> a version of <a href="https://hu.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gomoku" target="_blank">gomoku.</a></p>
        <p>To win, we need to put at least five of our puppets in a line, diagonally or vertically or horizontally.</p>
        <p>The amoeba is theoretically one of the board games, but in reality, children typically play on the checkered paper of a booklet with a pencil and pen.</p><br>
        <h1>Gameplay</h1>
        <p>The game is not much different from a gomok, except that the size of the board is not fixed, and so there can be no second round of play by pushing the pieces.</p>
        <p>The two players take turns placing a piece on the board. The object of the game is to place five of your own pieces without interruption in a horizontal, vertical, or diagonal direction.</p>
        <p>The opponent tries to prevent this with puppets placed at the end of the line that is likely to form.</p>
        <p>In the most typical version played on paper, one player replaces the pieces with X and the other with O, hence the name Ox in the game, although it is also used for Tic-tac-toe.</p><br>
        <h1>Quarto Online Amoeba</h1>
        <p>After the games played and won, the winner gets 20 points.</p>
        <p>If the opponent quits during the game, the player left in the game wins, but only gets 5 points.</p><br>
